1 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
2 2nd Session of the 60th Legislature (2026)
3 HOUSE BILL 4322 By: Kendrix
4
5
6 AS INTRODUCED
7 An Act relating to professions and occupations;
amending 59 O.S. 2021, Section 396.2, which relates
8 to the Funeral Services Licensing Act definitions;
modifying definition for funeral director in charge;
9 amending 59 O.S. 2021, Section 396.3, as last amended
by Section 1, Chapter 50, O.S.L. 2025 (59 O.S. Supp.
10 2025, Section 396.3), which relates to funeral
director in charge duties; removing requirement for
11 funeral directors to be dually licensed; and
providing an effective date.
12
13
14
15 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
16 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 396.2, is
17 amended to read as follows:
18 Section 396.2. As used in the Funeral Services Licensing Act:
19 1. "Embalmer" means a person who disinfects or preserves dead
20 human remains, entire or in part, by the use of chemical substances,
21 fluids or gases in the remains, or by the introduction of same into
22 the remains by vascular or hypodermic injection, or by direct
23 application into organs or cavities;
24 2. "Funeral director" means a person who:
Req. No. 14330 Page 1

1 a. is engaged in or conducts or represents themselves as
2 being engaged in preparing for the burial or disposal
3 and directing and supervising the burial or disposal
4 of dead human remains,
5 b. is engaged in or conducts or represents themselves as
6 being engaged in maintaining a funeral establishment
7 for the preparation and the disposition, or for the
8 care of dead human remains,
9 c. uses, in connection with the name of the person or
10 funeral establishment, the words "funeral director" or
11 "undertaker" or "mortician" or any other title
12 implying that the person is engaged as a funeral
13 director,
14 d. sells funeral service merchandise to the public, or
15 e. is responsible for the legal and ethical operation of
16 a crematory;
17 3. "Funeral establishment" means a place of business used in
18 the care and preparation for burial, commercial embalming, or
19 transportation of dead human remains, or any place where any person
20 or persons shall hold forth and be engaged in the profession of
21 undertaking or funeral directing;
22 4. "Apprentice" means a person who is engaged in learning the
23 practice of embalming or the practice of funeral directing, as the
24 case may be, under the instruction and personal supervision of a
Req. No. 14330 Page 2

1 duly licensed embalmer or a duly licensed funeral director of and in
2 the State of Oklahoma, pursuant to the provisions of the Funeral
3 Services Licensing Act, and who is duly registered as such with said
4 Board;
5 5. "Board" means the Oklahoma Funeral Board;
6 6. "Directing a funeral" or "funeral directing" means directing
7 funeral services from the time of the first call until final
8 disposition or release to a common carrier or release to next of kin
9 of the deceased or the designee of the next of kin;
10 7. "First call" means the beginning of the relationship and
11 duty of the funeral director to take charge of dead human remains
12 and have such remains prepared by embalming, cremation, or
13 otherwise, for burial or disposition, provided all laws pertaining
14 to public health in this state are complied with. First call does
15 not include calls made by ambulance, when the person dispatching the
16 ambulance does not know whether or not dead human remains are to be
17 picked up;
18 8. "Personal supervision" means the physical presence of a
19 licensed funeral director or embalmer at the specified time and
20 place of the providing of acts of funeral service;
21 9. "Commercial embalming establishment" means a fixed place of
22 business consisting of an equipped preparation room, and other rooms
23 as necessary, for the specified purpose of performing preparation
24
Req. No. 14330 Page 3

1 and shipping services of dead human remains to funeral
2 establishments inside and outside this state;
3 10. "Funeral service merchandise or funeral services" means
4 those products and services normally provided by funeral
5 establishments and required to be listed on the General Price List
6 of the Federal Trade Commission, 15 U.S.C., Section 57a(a),
7 including, but not limited to, the sale of burial supplies and
8 equipment, but excluding the sale by a cemetery of lands or
9 interests therein, services incidental thereto, markers, memorials,
10 monuments, equipment, crypts, niches or outer enclosures;
11 11. "Outer enclosure" means a grave liner, grave box, or grave
12 vault;
13 12. "Funeral director in charge" means an individual licensed
14 as both a funeral director and embalmer designated by a funeral
15 service establishment, commercial embalming establishment, or
16 crematory who is responsible for the legal and ethical operation of
17 the establishment and is accountable to the Board;
18 13. "Authorizing agent" means a person legally entitled to
19 order the cremation or final disposition of particular human remains
20 pursuant to Section 1151 or 1158 of Title 21 of the Oklahoma
21 Statutes;
22 14. "Cremation" means the technical process, using heat and
23 flame, or heat and pressure, that reduces human remains to essential
24 elements, including bone fragments. The reduction takes place
Req. No. 14330 Page 4

1 thro ugh heat and evaporation. Cremation shall include, but not be
2 limited to, the processing and pulverization of the bone fragments,
3 or through alkaline hydrolysis;
4 15. "Crematory" means a structure containing a furnace or
5 alkaline hydrolysis vessel used or intended to be used for the
6 cremation of human remains. The term includes a facility that
7 cremates human remains through alkaline hydrolysis; and
8 16. "Alkaline hydrolysis" means the reduction of human remains
9 to bone fragments and essential elements in a licensed crematory
10 using heat, pressure, water and base chemical agents.
11 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 59 O.S. 2021, Section 396.3, as
12 last amended by Section 1, Chapter 50, O.S.L. 2025 (59 O.S. Supp.
13 2025, Section 396.3), is amended to read as follows:
14 Section 396.3 A. The Oklahoma Funeral Board shall determine
15 the qualifications necessary to enable any person to practice as a
16 funeral director or embalmer, and prescribe the requirements for a
17 funeral establishment or commercial embalming establishment. The
18 Board shall examine all applicants for licenses to practice as a
19 funeral director or embalmer. The Board shall issue the proper
20 licenses to applicants who successfully pass such examination and
21 qualify pursuant to any additional requirements the Board may
22 prescribe.
23
24
Req. No. 14330 Page 5

1 B. 1. Except as provided in subsection C of this section, the
2 minimum requirements for a license to practice funeral directing or
3 embalming, or both, are as follows:
4 An applicant for a license to practice funeral directing or
5 embalming shall be at least eighteen (18) years of age, a legal
6 resident of this state, and a citizen or permanent resident of the
7 United States. In addition, an applicant shall be a graduate of a
8 program of mortuary science accredited by the American Board of
9 Funeral Service Education, and have served one (1) year as a
10 registered apprentice. The applicant may serve as a registered
11 apprentice prior to enrollment in an approved school of mortuary
12 science, or subsequent to graduation from the school, and pass any
13 of the following relevant exams necessary for licensure: the
14 International Conference of Funeral Service Examining Board National
15 Board Science Examination, the International Conference of Funeral
16 Service Examining Board National Board Arts Examination, the
17 Oklahoma Funeral Directors Examination, or the Oklahoma Embalmers
18 Examination with a seventy-five (75) or higher score on each exam.
19 2. Curriculum of study for an embalmer or funeral director is a
20 program of mortuary science which shall be that prescribed by the
21 American Board of Funeral Service Education.
22 C. 1. If a person chooses not to meet the qualifications in
23 subsection B of this section for a funeral director, the person may
24 alternatively qualify for a license to practice funeral directing,
Req. No. 14330 Page 6

1 but not embalming, upon meeting the eligibility requirements of this
2 subsection as follows:
3 An applicant for a license to practice funeral directing shall
4 be at least eighteen (18) years of age, a legal resident of this
5 state, and a citizen or permanent resident of the United States. An
6 applicant is required to complete a funeral director course of study
7 approved by the Oklahoma Funeral Board and that is administered by a
8 program of funeral service/mortuary science accredited by the
9 American Board of Funeral Service Education (ABFSE). The funeral
10 director course of study shall include at least thirty (30) semester
11 hours or equivalent closely following the ABFSE curriculum standard,
12 limited to only: Business Management, Cremation, Social
13 Sciences/Humanities, Legal, Ethical, Regulatory, plus essential
14 elements of embalming, restorative art, general concerns when
15 dealing with human remains, a practicum experience, and preparation
16 for the required board exams. In addition to the funeral director
17 course of study, the applicant is required to complete a twelve-
18 month minimum term as a registered apprentice with employment at a
19 licensed establishment and must have assisted with twenty-five
20 arrangement conferences and assisted with twenty-five separate
21 funeral or memorial services under the supervision of a licensed
22 funeral director in this state. The applicant may serve as a
23 registered apprentice prior to enrollment in an approved school of
24
Req. No. 14330 Page 7

1 mort uary science, concurrently while in mortuary school, or
2 subsequent to completion of the funeral director course of study.
3 2. Curriculum of study for a funeral director license shall be
4 in a program of mortuary science which shall be that prescribed by
5 the Oklahoma Funeral Board. An applicant must pay all fees as
6 provided in Section 396.4 of this title and pass an exam provided by
7 the International Conference of Funeral Service Examining Board or
8 the Oklahoma Funeral Directors Exam with a score of seventy-five
9 (75) or higher as well as pass a law exam provided by the Oklahoma
10 Funeral Board, with a score of seventy-five (75) or higher. A
11 license to practice as a funeral director issued pursuant to this
12 subsection shall be restricted to funeral director, and the licensee
13 shall not be eligible to practice as the funeral director in charge
14 as defined in Section 396.2 of this title.
15 3. If a person chooses not to meet the qualifications in
16 subsection B of this section for an embalmer, the person may
17 alternatively qualify for a license to practice embalming, upon
18 meeting the eligibility requirements of this subsection as follows:
19 An applicant for a license of this state, a citizen or permanent
20 resident of the United States, and of good moral character. An
21 applicant is required to complete an embalmer course of study
22 approved by the Oklahoma Funeral Board and that is administered by a
23 program of funeral service/mortuary science accredited by the
24 American Board of Funeral Service Education (ABFSE). The embalmer
Req. No. 14330 Page 8

1 cour se of study shall include at least thirty (30) semester hours or
2 equivalent closely following the ABFSE curriculum standard, limited
3 to only: Biology, Chemistry, Microbiology, Human Anatomy,
4 Pathology, Embalming, Embalming Chemistry, and Restorative Art, plus
5 essential elements of grief, communication, and preparation for the
6 required board examinations. The applicant must also complete a
7 twelve-month minimum term as a registered apprentice with full-time
8 employment at a licensed establishment or licensed commercial
9 embalming establishment and must have assisted with twenty-five
10 embalmings under the supervision of a licensed embalmer in this
11 state. The applicant may serve as a registered apprentice prior to
12 enrollment in an approved school of mortuary science, concurrently
13 while in mortuary school, or subsequent to completion of the
14 embalmer course of study.
15 4. Curriculum of study for an embalmer license shall be in a
16 program of funeral service/mortuary science which shall be that
17 prescribed by the Oklahoma Funeral Board. An applicant must pay all
18 fees as provided in Section 396.4 of this title and pass the
19 embalmer examination provided by the International Conference of
20 Funeral Service Examining Board or the Oklahoma Embalmers Exam with
21 a score of seventy-five (75) or higher as well as pass a law exam
22 provided by the Oklahoma Funeral Board with a score of seventy-five
23 (75) or higher. A license to practice as an embalmer issued
24 pursuant to this subsection shall be restricted to embalmer, and the
Req. No. 14330 Page 9

1 lice nsee shall not be eligible to practice as the funeral director
2 in charge as defined in Section 396.2 of this title.
3 D. The Board shall issue the appropriate license to any
4 qualified applicant whose application has been approved by the
5 Board, and who has paid the fees required by Section 396.4 of this
6 title, has passed the required examinations with a seventy-five (75)
7 or higher score and has demonstrated to the Board proficiency as an
8 embalmer or funeral director.
9 E. The Board shall maintain for public inspection a list of all
10 accredited schools of embalming and mortuary science.
11 F. Each funeral director in charge as defined in Section 396.2
12 of this title shall have a current dual funeral director and
13 embalmer license. A funeral director in charge of a funeral service
14 establishment or crematory that does not have a current dual funeral
15 director and embalmer license on the effective date of this act
16 shall be considered to be grandfathered and may serve as funeral
17 director in charge of any funeral service establishment or crematory
18 in accordance with rules prescribed by the Board, but shall not
19 serve as funeral director in charge of a commercial embalming
20 establishment which shall require a current dual funeral director
21 and embalmer license.
22 G. F. Upon April 23, 2021, and for one (1) year thereafter, the
23 Board may issue a temporary funeral director or embalmer license in
24
Req. No. 14330 Page 10

1 the event a statewide state of emergency is declared by the Governor
2 and during such time as the state of emergency is in effect.
3 SECTION 3. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
